mful climate impacts]], which a number of nations have signed. Limiting global temperature increase to 2 degrees Celsius, thought to be a risk by the [[Stockholm Environmental Institute|SEI]], is now doubtful.\n\nTo limit global temperature to a hypothetical 2 degrees Celsius rise would demand a 75% decline in [[carbon emissions]] in industrial countries by 2050, if the population is 10 billion in 2050.<ref>Energil\u00e4get 2050 by prof. Cristian Azar and Kristian Lindgren [[Chalmers University of Technology|Chalmers]] [[G\u00f6teborg]] {{in lang|sv}}</ref> Across 40 years, this averages to a 2% decrease every year. In 2011, the emissions of energy production continued rising regardless of the consensus of the basic problem. Hypothetically, according to [[Robert Engelman]] (Worldwatch Institute), in order to prevent collapse, human civilization would have to stop increasing emissions within a decade regardless of the economy or population (2009).<ref>''State of the world 2009'', [[Worldwatch Institute]]</ref>\n\n[[Greenhouse gases]] are not the only emissions of energy production and consumption. Large amounts of pollutants such as [[sulphurous oxide]]s (SO<sub>x</sub>), [[nitrous oxide]]s (NO<sub>x</sub>), and [[particulate matter]] (PM) are produced from the combustion of fossil fuels and biomass; the [[World Health Organization]] estimates that 7 million premature deaths are caused each year by [[air pollution]].<ref name=\"who.int\">{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2014/air-pollution/en/|title=7 million premature deaths annually linked to air pollution|publisher=WHO}}</ref> [[Biomass]] [[combustion]] is a major contributor.<ref name=\"who.int\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs313/en/|title= Ambient (outdoor) air quality and health|publisher=WHO}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs292/en/|title=Household air pollution and health |publisher=WHO}}</ref> In addition to producing air pollution like [[fossil fuel]] combustion, most biomass has high CO<sub>2</sub> emissions.<ref>http://www.pfpi.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/PFPI-biomass-carbon-accounting-overview_April.pdf</ref>\n\n== By source ==\n<!-- pie chart -->\n{{Pie chart\n| thumb =right\n| caption =Total primary energy supply of  13,972 [[mega-]][[tonne of oil equivalent|toe]] by source in 2017 (IEA, 2019)<ref name=\"IEA-Report-keyworld-2019\"/>\n| other = \n| label1 =Oil\n| value1 =32.0\n| color1 =#7C6250\n| label2 =Coal/peat/shale\n| value2 =27.1\n| color2 =#313c42 \n| label3 =Natural gas\n| value3 =22.2\n| color3 =#ef8e39\n| label4 =Biofuels and waste\n| value4 =9.5\n| color4 =#ABFF57\n| label5 = Hydro electricity\n| value5 =2.5\n| color5 =#FF57FF\n| label6 =Others ([[Renewable energy|renewables]])\n| value6 =1.8\n| color6 =#00CC4B\n| label7 =Nuclear\n| value7 =4.9\n| color7 =#de2821\n}}\n\n=== Fossil fuels ===\n{{Main|Fossil fuel}}\n\nThe twentieth century saw a rapid twenty-fold increase in the use of fossil fuels. Between 1980 and 2006, the worldwide annual growth rate was 2%.<ref name=EIA/> According to the US [[Energy Information Administration]]'s 2006 estimate, the estimated 471.8&nbsp;EJ total consumption in 2004, was divided as given in the table above, with fossil fuels supplying 86% of the world's energy:\n\n====Coal====\n{{Main|Coal|List of countries by coal production}}\n\nIn 2000, China accounted for 28% of world coal consumption, other Asia consumed 19%, North America 25% and the EU 14%. The single greatest coal-consuming country is China. Its share of the world coal production was 28% in 2000 and rose to 48% in 2009. In contrast to China's ~70% increase in coal consumption, world coal use increased 48% from 2000 to 2009. In practice, the majority of this growth occurred in China and the rest in other Asia.<ref name=\"energisve2010Coal\"/> China's energy consumption is mostly driven by the industry sector, the majority of which comes from coal consumption.<ref>Ma, Damien. \"China's Coming Decade of Natural Gas\". ''Asia's Uncertain LNG Future, NBR Special Report''. November 2013. Retrieved 8 August 2014.</ref>\n\nWorld annual coal production increased 1,905&nbsp;Mt or 32% in 6 years in 2011 compared to 2005, of which over 70% was in China and 8% in India. Coal production was in 2011 7,783&nbsp;Mt, and 2009 6,903&nbsp;Mt, equal to 12.7% production increase in two years.<ref>Key statistics 2012, 2010 and 2006 IEA</ref>\n\nIf production and consumption of coal continue at the rate as in 2008, proven and economically recoverable world reserves of coal would last for about 150 years. This is much more than needed for an irreversible climate catastrophe. Coal is the largest source of [[carbon dioxide]] emissions in the world. According to [[James Hansen]] the single most important action needed to tackle the climate crisis is to reduce CO<sub>2</sub> emissions from [[Coal mining|coal]].<ref>[http://www.greenpeace.org/raw/content/international/press/reports/true-cost-coal.pdf The True Cost of Coal] 27 November 2008 pp. 66\u201369</ref> [[Energy in Indonesia|Indonesia]] and [[Energy in Australia|Australia]] exported together 57.1% of the world coal export in 2011. China, Japan, South Korea, India and Taiwan had 65% share of all the world coal import in 2011.<ref>Key statistics 2012 IEA</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatleft\" style=\"text-align: right; margin-left: 22px;\"\n|+ {{nowrap|Regional coal supply (TWh), share 2010 (%) and share of change 2000\u20132010<ref name=energisve2010Coal>Table 52 Global supply of coal, 1990\u20132009 (pp. 44-45), in {{cite web|title=Energy in Sweden \u2014 facts and figures 2010|url=https://webbshop.cm.se/System/DownloadResource.ashx?p=Energimyndigheten&rl=default:/Resources/Permanent/Static/e0a2619a83294099a16519a0b5edd26f/ET2010_46.pdf|publisher=Swedish Energy Agency|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014221749/http://webbshop.cm.se/System/DownloadResource.ashx?p=Energimyndigheten&rl=default%3A%2FResources%2FPermanent%2FStatic%2Fe0a2619a83294099a16519a0b5edd26f%2FET2010_46.pdf|archivedate=14 October 2013|url-status=dead}} (see also [https://energimyndigheten.a-w2m.se/FolderContents.mvc/Download?ResourceId=2609 Energy in Sweden 2011]), data from [[International Energy Agency|IEA]] [https://www.iea.org/statistics/relateddatabases/energybalancesofnon-oecdcountries/ Energy Balances of Non-OECD countries] 2010.</ref><ref name=\"Energil\u00e4get 2011\">[http://energimyndigheten.se/Global/Statistik/Energil%C3%A4get/Energil%C3%A4get%20i%20siffror%202011.pdf Energil\u00e4get 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401205225/http://www.energimyndigheten.se/Global/Statistik/Energil%C3%A4get/Energil%C3%A4get%20i%20siffror%202011.pdf |date=1 April 2012 }}</ref>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Region\n! scope=\"col\" | 2000\n! scope=\"col\" | 2008\n! scope=\"col\" | 2009*\n! scope=\"col\" | 2010*\n! scope=\"col\" | %*\n! scope=\"col\" | Change<br/>2000\u20132009*\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | North America\n|  6,654 ||  6,740 ||  6,375 ||  6,470 ||  16% || \u22121.2%\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Asia excl. China\n|  5,013 ||  7,485 ||  7,370 ||  7,806 ||  19% || 18.9%\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | China\n|  7,318 || 16,437 || 18,449 || 19,928 ||  48% || 85.5%\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | EU\n|  3,700 ||  3,499 ||  3,135 ||  3,137 ||   8% || \u22123.8%\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Africa\n|  1,049 ||  1,213 ||  1,288 ||  1,109 ||   3% ||  0.4%\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Russia\n|  1,387 ||  1,359 ||    994 ||  1,091 ||   3% || \u22122.0%\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Others\n|  1,485 ||  1,763 ||  1,727 ||  1,812 ||   4% ||  2.2%\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold;\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Total\n| 26,607 || 38,497 || 39,340 || 41,354 || 100% ||  47.9%\n|- style=\"text-align:left;font-size:smaller;\"\n| colspan=7 | Source: IEA, *in 2009, 2010 BP<br/>*Change 2000\u20132009: Region's share of the world change +12,733&nbsp;TWh from 2000 to 2009\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"text-align: right;  margin-left: 22px;\"\n|+ Top 10 coal exporters (Mt)<ref name=IEA2013>\nIEA Key World Energy Statistics\n[http://www.iea.org/publications/freepublications/publication/name,31287,en.html 2013], [http://www.iea.org/publications/freepublications/publication/kwes.pdf 2012], [http://www.iea.org/textbase/nppdf/free/2011/key_world_energy_stats.pdf 2011], [http://www.iea.org/textbase/nppdf/free/2010/key_stats_2010.pdf 2010], [http://www.iea.org/textbase/nppdf/free/2009/key2009.pdf 2009] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007042901/http://www.iea.org/textbase/nppdf/free/2009/key2009.pdf |date=7 October 2013 }}, [http://www.iea.org/textbase/nppdf/free/2006/key2006.pdf 2006] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091012043312/http://www.iea.org/textbase/nppdf/free/2006/key2006.pdf |date=12 October 2009 }} [[International Energy Agency|IEA]] October, crude oil p. 11, coal p. 13, gas p. 15\n</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank\n! scope=\"col\" | Nation\n! scope=\"col\" | 2010\n! scope=\"col\" | 2011\n! scope=\"col\" | Share<br/>% 2011\n! scope=\"col\" | 2012\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Indonesia|Indonesia]]\n|   162 ||   309 || 29.7% ||   383\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Australia|Australia]]\n|   298 ||   285 || 27.4% ||   302\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Russia|Russia]]\n|    89 ||    99 ||  9.5% ||   103\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in the United States|US]]\n|    57 ||    85 ||  8.2% ||   106\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Colombia|Colombia]]\n|    68 ||    76 ||  7.3% ||    82\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in South Africa|South Africa]]\n|    68 ||    70 ||  6.7% ||    72\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Kazakhstan|Kazakhstan]]\n|    33 ||    34 ||  3.3% ||    32\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Canada|Canada]]\n|    24 ||    24 ||  2.3% ||    25\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Vietnam|Vietnam]]\n|    21 ||    23 ||  2.2% ||    18\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[:Category:Energy in Mongolia|Mongolia]]\n|    17 ||    22 ||  2.1% ||    22\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | x\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Others\n|    19 ||    14 ||  1.3% ||\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold;\"\n! scope=\"row\" colspan=2 style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Total (Mt)\n|   856 || 1,041 ||       || 1,168\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" colspan=2 | Top ten\n| 97.8% || 98.7% ||       ||\n|}\n{{clear left}}\n\n==== Oil ====\n{{Main|Petroleum|List of countries by oil production|List of countries by oil consumption}}\n\nCoal fueled the industrial revolution in the 18th and 19th century. With the advent of the automobile, aeroplanes and the spreading use of electricity, [[Petroleum|oil]] became the dominant fuel during the twentieth century. The growth of oil as the largest fossil fuel was further enabled by steadily dropping prices from 1920 until 1973. After the oil shocks of [[1973 oil crisis|1973]] and [[1979 energy crisis|1979]], during which the price of oil increased from 5 to 45 US dollars per barrel, there was a shift away from oil.<ref>Yergin, p. 792</ref> Coal, natural gas, and nuclear became the fuels of choice for electricity generation and conservation measures increased energy efficiency. In the U.S. the average car more than doubled the number of miles per gallon. Japan, which bore the brunt of the oil shocks, made spectacular improvements and now has the highest energy efficiency in the world.<ref name = \"IEAKey\">{{cite web |url= http://www.iea.org/textbase/nppdf/free/2006/key2006.pdf |publisher= International Energy Agency |title= Key World Energy Statistics |year= 2006 |accessdate= 3 April 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20091012043312/http://www.iea.org/textbase/nppdf/free/2006/key2006.pdf |archive-date= 12 October 2009 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }} pp. 48\u201357</ref> From 1965 to 2008, the use of fossil fuels has continued to grow and their share of the energy supply has increased. From 2003 to 2008, coal was the fastest growing fossil fuel.<ref>Yergin, p. ?</ref><!-- Page numbers needed on book sources -->\n\nIt is estimated that between 100 and 135 billion tonnes of oil has been consumed between 1850 and the present.<ref>[https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2009/05/090507072830.htm How Much Oil Have We Used?], [[Science Daily]], 8 May 2009. Retrieved March 2014.</ref>\n\n==== Natural Gas ====\n{{Main|Natural Gas|List of countries by natural gas production|List of countries by natural gas consumption}}\n\nIn 2009, the world use of natural gas grew 31% compared to 2000. 66% of this growth was outside EU, North America, Latin America, and Russia. Others include the Middle East, Asia, and Africa. The gas supply increased also in the previous regions: 8.6% in the EU and 16% in the North America 2000\u20132009.<ref name=\"energil\u00e4get2010G\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: right; margin-left: 22px;\"\n|+ Regional gas supply (TWh) and share 2010 (%)<ref name=\"Energil\u00e4get 2011\"/><ref name=\"energil\u00e4get2010G\">Table 50 Global supply of gas 1990\u20132009 (p. 44), in {{cite web|title=Energy in Sweden \u2014 facts and figures 2010|url=https://webbshop.cm.se/System/DownloadResource.ashx?p=Energimyndigheten&rl=default:/Resources/Permanent/Static/e0a2619a83294099a16519a0b5edd26f/ET2010_46.pdf|publisher=Swedish Energy Agency|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014221749/http://webbshop.cm.se/System/DownloadResource.ashx?p=Energimyndigheten&rl=default%3A%2FResources%2FPermanent%2FStatic%2Fe0a2619a83294099a16519a0b5edd26f%2FET2010_46.pdf|archivedate=14 October 2013|url-status=dead}} (see also [https://energimyndigheten.a-w2m.se/FolderContents.mvc/Download?ResourceId=2609 Energy in Sweden 2011]), data from [[International Energy Agency|IEA]] [https://www.iea.org/statistics/relateddatabases/energybalancesofnon-oecdcountries/ Energy Balances of Non-OECD countries] 2010.</ref>\n|-\n! Land\n! 2000\n! 2008\n! 2009\n! 2010\n! %\n|-\n| align=left | North America\n| 7,621 ||  7,779 ||  8,839 ||  8,925 || 27%\n|-\n| align=left | Asia excl. China\n|  2,744 ||  4,074 ||  4,348 ||  4,799 || 14%\n|-\n| align=left | [[Energy in China|China]]\n|    270 ||    825 ||  1,015 ||  1,141 ||  3%\n|-\n| align=left | [[Energy in the European Union|EU]]\n|  4,574 ||  5,107 ||  4,967 ||  5,155 ||  16%\n|-\n| align=left | [[Energy in Africa|Africa]]\n|    612 ||    974 ||  1,455 ||  1,099 ||  3%\n|-\n| align=left | [[Energy in Russia|Russia]]\n|  3,709 ||  4,259 ||  4,209 ||  4,335 || 13%\n|-\n| align=left | Latin America\n|  1,008 ||  1,357 ||    958 || nd || nd\n|-\n| align=left | Others\n|  3,774 ||  5,745 ||  6,047 ||  7,785 ||  23%\n|- \n! Total !! 24,312 !! 30,134 !! 31,837 !! 33,240 !! 100%\n|-\n| colspan=6 style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 0.85em; padding: 6px 3px;\"| Source: IEA, in 2009, 2010 BP\n|}\n\n===Nuclear power===\n{{Main|Nuclear Power}}\n\nAs of 1 July 2016, the world had 444 operable grid-electric nuclear fission power reactors with 62 others under construction.<ref name=\"WNA2016\">[[World Nuclear Association]], (1 July 2016) [http://www.world-nuclear.org/information-library/facts-and-figures/world-nuclear-power-reactors-and-uranium-requireme.aspx], www.world-nuclear.org</ref>\n\nAnnual generation of nuclear power has been on a slight downward trend since 2007, decreasing 1.8% in 2009 to 2558&nbsp;TWh, and another 1.6% in 2011 to 2518&nbsp;TWh, despite increases in production from most countries worldwide, because those increases were more than offset by decreases in Germany and Japan. Nuclear power met 11.7% of the world's electricity demand in 2011. Source: IEA/OECD.<ref name=\"IEA-Report-2013\"/>\n\nWhile all the commercial reactors today use [[nuclear fission]] energy, there are plans to use [[nuclear fusion]] energy for future power plants. \nSeveral international nuclear fusion reactor experiments exists or are being constructed, including [[ITER]].\n\n=== Renewable energy ===\n{{Main|Renewable energy|List of renewable energy topics by country|Renewable energy commercialization}}\n\n{{multiple image\n |direction =  horizontal\n |align = right\n |width1 = 220\n |width2 = 180\n |image1=Global public support for energy sources (Ipsos 2011).png\n |image2=\n |caption1=Strong public support for [[renewables]] worldwide in 2011<ref name=\"ipsos 2011 preference for renewables\">{{harvnb|Ipsos|2011|p=3}}</ref>\n |caption2=Comparison of global potential of the world's [[energy source]]s\n}}\n\nRenewable energy is generally defined as energy that comes from [[Renewable resource|resources]] that are not significantly depleted by their use, such as [[sunlight]], [[wind]], [[rain]], [[tidal power|tides]], [[wave power|waves]] and [[geothermal energy|geothermal heat]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://thebulletin.org/myth-renewable-energy |title= The myth of renewable energy |work= Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists |date= 22 November 2011 |accessdate= 3 October 2013 }}</ref> Renewable energy is gradually replacing conventional fuels in four distinct areas: [[electricity generation]], [[solar hot water|hot water]]/[[space heating]], [[motor fuel]]s, and [[Stand-alone power system|rural (off-grid)]] energy services.<ref name=ren15>REN21 (2010). [http://www.harbortaxgroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/REN21_GSR_2010_full_revised-Sept2010.pdf Renewables 2010 Global Status Report] p. 15.</ref>\n\nBased on [[REN21]]'s 2019 report, renewables contributed 18.1 percent to the world's energy consumption and 26 percent to its electricity generation in 2017 and 2018, respectively. This energy consumption is divided as 7.5% coming from traditional biomass, 4.2% as heat energy (non-biomass), 1% biofuels for transport, 3.6% hydro electricity and 2% electricity from wind, solar, biomass, geothermal, and ocean power. Worldwide investments in renewable technologies amounted to more than US$289 billion in 2018, with countries like [[Renewable energy in China|China]] and the [[Renewable energy in the United States|United States]] heavily investing in wind, hydro, solar and biofuels.<ref name=\"ria21-GSR2014\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ren21.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/gsr_2019_full_report_en.pdf|title=Renewables 2019: Global Status Report|author=REN21|author-link=REN21|year=2019|website=|pages=|url-status=live|archiveurl=|archivedate=|access-date=|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Renewable energy resources exist over wide geographical areas, in contrast to other energy sources, which are concentrated in a limited number of countries. Rapid deployment of renewable energy and [[efficient energy use|energy efficiency]] is resulting in significant [[Energy security and renewable technology|energy security]], [[climate change mitigation]], and economic benefits.<ref name=\"International Energy Agency 2012\">{{cite web |url= http://www.iea.org/Textbase/npsum/ETP2012SUM.pdf |title= Energy Technology Perspectives 2012 |author= International Energy Agency |year= 2012 |website= }}</ref> In international public opinion surveys there is strong support for promoting renewable sources such as solar power and wind power.<ref name=\"UNEP\">{{cite web |title= Global Trends in Sustainable Energy Investment 2007: Analysis of Trends and Issues in the Financing of Renewable Energy and Energy Efficiency in OECD and Developing Countries |url= http://www.unep.org/pdf/72_Glob_Sust_Energy_Inv_Report_(2007).pdf |website= www.unep.org |publisher= United Nations Environment Programme |accessdate= 13 October 2014 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304114134/http://www.unep.org/pdf/72_Glob_Sust_Energy_Inv_Report_(2007).pdf |archivedate= 4 March 2016 |page= 3 |year= 2007 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}</ref> At the national level, at least 30 nations around the world already have renewable energy contributing more than 20 percent of energy supply. National renewable energy markets are projected to continue to grow strongly in the coming decade and beyond.<ref name=\"REN21 2013\">{{cite web |url= http://new.ren21.net/Portals/0/REN21_GFR_2013_print.pdf |title= Renewables global futures report 2013 |author= REN21 |year= 2013 |website=  }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe following table shows increasing [[nameplate capacity]], and has [[capacity factor]]s that range from 11% for solar, to 40% for hydropower.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://meteolcd.wordpress.com/2015/09/21/electricity-generation-very-different-capacity-factors/|title=Electricity generation: very different capacity factors!|date=21 September 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: right; \"\n|-\n! Selected renewable energy global indicators !! 2008 !! 2009 !! 2010 !! 2011 !! 2012 || 2013 !! 2014 !! 2015 \n!2016\n!2017\n!2018\n|-\n| align=left | Investment in new renewable capacity (annual) (10<sup>9</sup> USD)<ref>http://www.ren21.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/GSR2015_Figure25.jpg</ref> || 182 || 178 || 237 || 279 || 256 ||232 || 270 || 285\n|241\n|279\n|289\n|-\n| align=left | Renewables power capacity (existing) (GWe) || 1,140 || 1,230 || 1,320 || 1,360 || 1,470 || 1,578 || 1,712 || 1,849\n|2,017\n|2,195\n|2,378\n|-\n| align=left | Hydropower capacity (existing) (GWe) || 885 || 915 || 945 || 970 || 990 || 1,018 || 1,055 || 1,064\n|1,096\n|1,114\n|1,132\n|-\n| align=left | Wind power capacity (existing) (GWe) || 121 || 159 || 198 || 238 || 283 || 319 || 370 || 433\n|487\n|539\n|591\n|-\n| align=left | Solar PV capacity (grid-connected) (GWe) || 16 || 23 || 40 || 70 || 100 || 138 || 177 || 227\n|303\n|402\n|505\n|-\n| align=left | Solar hot water capacity (existing) (GWth) || 130 || 160 || 185 || 232 || 255 || 373 || 406 || 435\n|456\n|472\n|480\n|-\n| align=left | Ethanol production (annual) (10<sup>9</sup> litres) || 67 || 76 || 86 || 86 || 83 ||87 ||94 || 98\n|98\n|106\n|112\n|-\n| align=left | Biodiesel production (annual) (10<sup>9</sup> litres) || 12 || 17.8 || 18.5 || 21.4 || 22.5 ||26 || 29.7 || 30\n|30\n|31\n|34\n|-\n| align=left | Countries with policy targets <br /> for renewable energy use || 79 || 89 || 98 || 118 || 138 ||144 ||164 ||173\n|176\n|179\n|169\n|-\n! colspan=\"12\" style=\"font-weight: normal; font-size: 0.85em; text-align: left; padding: 6px 0 4px 4px;\" | ''Source:'' The Renewable Energy Policy Network for the 21st Century ([[REN21]])\u2013Global Status Report<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ren21.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/GSR2011_Full-Report_English.pdf|title=Renewables 2011: Global Status Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ren21.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/GSR2012_Full-Report_English.pdf|title=Renewables 2012: Global Status Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ren21.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/GSR2013_Full-Report_English.pdf|title=Renewables 2013: Global Status Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ren21.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/GSR2014_Key-Findings_English.pdf|title=Renewables 2014: Global Status Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ren21.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/GSR2015_Full-Report_English.pdf|title=Renewables 2015: Global Status Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ren21.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/REN21_GSR2016_FullReport_en_11.pdf|title=Renewables 2016: Global Status Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ren21.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/GSR2017_Full-Report_English.pdf|title=Renewables 2017: Global Status Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ren21.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Full-Report-2018.pdf|title=Renewables 2018: Global Status Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ren21.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/gsr_2019_full_report_en.pdf|title=Renewables 2019: Global Status Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: right; \"\n|+ Renewable energy 2000-2013 (TWh)<ref>[http://www.energimyndigheten.se/nyhetsarkiv/2016/nu-finns-energilaget-i-siffror-2016/ Energil\u00e4get i siffror 2016] Energimyndigheten Sweden (See Renewable energy 12.3 Total energy 12.1)</ref>\n|-\n! \n! 2000\n! 2010\n! 2013\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| North-America || 1,973 || 2,237 || 2,443\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| EU || 1,204 || 2,093 || 2,428\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| Russia || align=right |245 || 239 || 271\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| China || 2,613\t|| 3,374 || 3,847\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| Asia (-China) || 4,147 || 4,996 || 5,361\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| Africa || 2,966\t|| 3,930 || 4,304\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| Latin America || 1 502 || 2,127|| 2,242\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Other || 567 || 670 || 738\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Total renewable ||  15,237 || 19,711|| 21,685\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Total energy||  116,958 || 148,736 || 157,485\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Share || 13.0%|| 13.3%|| 13.8%\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Total nonrenewable || 101,721  || 129,025 || 135,800 \n|-\n|}\n\nFrom 2000 to 2013 the total renewable energy use has increased by 6,450 TWh and total energy use by 40,500 TWh.\n\n==== Hydro ====\n{{Main|Hydroelectricity|Hydropower}}\n\nHydroelectricity is the term referring to electricity generated by [[hydropower]]; the production of electrical power through the use of the kinetic energy of falling or flowing water. In 2015 hydropower generated 16.6% of the world's total electricity and 70% of all renewable electricity,<ref>http://www.ren21.net/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/GSR_2016_Full_Report_REN21.pdf</ref> which continues the rapid rate of increase experienced between 2003 and 2009.<ref name=wi2012/> Hydropower is produced in 150 countries, with the Asia-Pacific region generating 32 percent of global hydropower in 2010. China is the largest hydroelectricity producer, with {{convert|721|TWh|PJ|abbr=on|order=flip}} of production in 2010, representing around 17% of domestic electricity use. There are now three hydroelectricity plants larger than 10&nbsp;GW: the [[Three Gorges Dam]] in China, [[Itaipu Dam]] in Brazil, and [[Guri Dam]] in Venezuela.<ref name=wi2012>{{cite web |url= http://www.worldwatch.org/node/9527 |title= Use and Capacity of Global Hydropower Increases |publisher= Worldwatch Institute |date= January 2012}}</ref> Nine of the [[List of countries by electricity production from renewable sources|worlds top 10 renewable electricity producers]] are primarily hydroelectric, one is wind.\n\n==== Marine energy ====\n{{Main|Ocean energy}}\n[[Marine energy]], also known as ''ocean energy'' and ''marine and hydrokinetic energy'' (MHK) includes [[tidal power|tidal]] and [[wave power|wave]] power and is a relatively new sector of renewable energy, with most projects still in the pilot phase, but the theoretical potential is equivalent to 4\u201318 million tonne of oil equivalent (toe). MHK development in U.S. and international waters includes projects using devices such as, wave energy converters in open coastal areas with significant waves, tidal turbines placed in coastal and estuarine areas, in-stream [[turbine]]s in fast-moving [[river]]s, ocean current turbines in areas of strong [[marine current]]s, and [[ocean thermal energy converter]]s in deep tropical waters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tethys.pnnl.gov/|title=Tethys &#124; Environmental Effects of Wind and Marine Renewable Energy|website=tethys.pnnl.gov|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Wind ====\n{{Main|Wind power|Wind power by country}}\n\nWind power is growing at the rate of 17% annually, with a worldwide [[Installed wind power capacity|installed capacity]] of 432,883&nbsp;megawatts (MW) at the end of 2015,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gwec.net/global-figures/graphs/ |title= GWEC Global Statistics |author= Global Wind Energy Council }}</ref><ref name=\"greeninc.blogs.nytimes.com\">Lars Kroldrup. [http://greeninc.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/02/15/gains-in-global-wind-capacity-reported/ Gains in Global Wind Capacity Reported] ''Green Inc.'', 15 February 2010.</ref><ref name=\"REN21 2011 15 2\">{{cite web |url= http://www.ren21.net/Portals/97/documents/GSR/GSR2011_Master18.pdf |title= Renewables 2011: Global Status Report |author= REN21 |year= 2011 |page= 15 |author-link= REN21 }}</ref> and is widely used in [[Wind power in the European Union|Europe]], [[Wind power in China|Asia]], and the [[Wind power in the United States|United States]].<ref name=\"Glob\">[http://www.gwec.net/uploads/media/07-02_PR_Global_Statistics_2006.pdf Global wind energy markets continue to boom \u2013 2006 another record year] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110407175732/http://www.gwec.net/uploads/media/07-02_PR_Global_Statistics_2006.pdf |date=7 April 2011 }} (PDF).</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.renewableenergyworld.com/rea/news/article/2011/03/wind-power-china-picks-up-paceeu-and-us-fall-but-global-market-grows |title= Wind Power: China Picks Up Pace |first= David |last= Beattie |date= 18 March 2011 |work= Renewable Energy World |publisher= }}</ref> Several countries have achieved relatively high levels of wind power penetration, such as 21% of stationary electricity production in [[Wind power in Denmark|Denmark]],<ref name=\"wwea\">{{cite web |publisher= [[World Wind Energy Association]] |title= World Wind Energy Report 2010 |work= Report |date= February 2011 |url= http://www.wwindea.org/home/images/stories/pdfs/worldwindenergyreport2010_s.pdf |accessdate= 30 April 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110904232058/http://www.wwindea.org/home/images/stories/pdfs/worldwindenergyreport2010_s.pdf |archivedate= 4 September 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> 18% in [[Wind power in Portugal|Portugal]],<ref name=\"wwea\"/> 16% in [[Wind power in Spain|Spain]],<ref name=\"wwea\"/> 14% in [[Wind power in Ireland|Ireland]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.eirgrid.com/renewables/ |title= Renewables |publisher= eirgrid.com |accessdate= 22 November 2010 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110810081403/http://www.eirgrid.com/renewables/ |archivedate= 10 August 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> and 9% in [[Wind power in Germany|Germany]] in 2010.<ref name=\"wwea\"/><ref name=ren212011>{{cite web |url= http://www.ren21.net/Portals/97/documents/GSR/GSR2011_Master18.pdf |title= Renewables 2011: Global Status Report |author= REN21 |year= 2011 |page= 11 |author-link= REN21 }}</ref> As of 2011, 83 countries around the world are using wind power on a commercial basis.<ref name=ren212011/> Continuing strong growth, by 2016 wind generated 3% of global power annually.<ref>http://www.bp.com/en/global/corporate/energy-economics/statistical-review-of-world-energy/renewable-energy/wind-energy.html</ref>\n\n==== Solar ====\n{{Main|Solar energy|Solar power|Solar power by country}}\n\nSolar energy, radiant [[light]] and [[heat]] from the [[sun]], has been harnessed by humans since [[ancient history|ancient times]] using a range of ever-evolving technologies. Solar energy technologies include [[solar heating]], [[solar photovoltaics]], [[concentrated solar power]] and [[solar architecture]], which can make considerable contributions to solving some of the most urgent problems the world now faces. The [[International Energy Agency]] projected that solar power could provide \"a third of the global final energy demand after 2060, while CO<sub>2</sub> emissions would be reduced to very low levels.\"<ref>http://www.iea.org/Textbase/npsum/solar2011SUM.pdf</ref> Solar technologies are broadly characterized as either [[passive solar]] or [[active solar]] depending on the way they capture, convert and distribute solar energy. Active solar techniques include the use of [[photovoltaic system]]s and [[solar thermal collector]]s to harness the energy. Passive solar techniques include orienting a building to the Sun, selecting materials with favorable [[thermal mass]] or light dispersing properties, and designing spaces that [[Ventilation (architecture)|naturally circulate air]]. From 2012 to 2016 solar capacity tripled and now provides 1.3% of global energy.<ref>http://www.bp.com/en/global/corporate/energy-economics/statistical-review-of-world-energy/renewable-energy/solar-energy.html</ref>\n\n==== Geothermal ====\n{{Main|Geothermal energy|Geothermal power}}\n\n[[Geothermal energy]] is used commercially in over 70 countries.<ref name=\"INEL\">{{cite web |publisher= [[MIT]] |title= The Future of Geothermal Energy |url= http://geothermal.inel.gov/publications/future_of_geothermal_energy.pdf |accessdate= 7 February 2007 |archive-url= https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20110310030646/http://geothermal.inel.gov/publications/future_of_geothermal_energy.pdf |archive-date= 10 March 2011 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> In 2004, {{convert|200|PJ|TWh}} of electricity was generated from geothermal resources, and an additional {{convert|270|PJ|TWh}} of geothermal energy was used directly, mostly for space heating. In 2007, the world had a global capacity for {{val|10|u=GW}} of electricity generation and an additional {{val|28|u=GW}} of [[geothermal heating|direct heating]], including extraction by [[geothermal heat pumps]].<ref name=\"Renewables2006\">{{cite web |url= http://www.ren21.net/globalstatusreport/download/RE_GSR_2006_Update.pdf |publisher= Renewable Energy Policy Network for the 21st century |title= Renewables, Global Status Report 2006 |year= 2006 |accessdate= 3 April 2007 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110718181410/http://www.ren21.net/globalstatusreport/download/RE_GSR_2006_Update.pdf |archivedate= 18 July 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"GEO\">{{cite journal |first1= Ingvar B. |last1= Fridleifsson |first2= Ruggero |last2= Bertani |first3= Ernst |last3= Huenges |first4= John W. |last4= Lund |first5= Arni |last5= Ragnarsson |first6= Ladislaus |last6= Rybach |date= 11 February 2008 |title= The possible role and contribution of geothermal energy to the mitigation of climate change |conference= IPCC Scoping Meeting on Renewable Energy Sources |editor= O. Hohmeyer and T. Trittin |location= Luebeck, Germany |pages= 59\u201380 |url= http://iga.igg.cnr.it/documenti/IGA/Fridleifsson_et_al_IPCC_Geothermal_paper_2008.pdf |accessdate= 6 April 2009 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110722030340/http://iga.igg.cnr.it/documenti/IGA/Fridleifsson_et_al_IPCC_Geothermal_paper_2008.pdf |archivedate= 22 July 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Heat pumps are small and widely distributed, so estimates of their total capacity are uncertain and range up to {{val|100|u=GW}}.<ref name=\"INEL\" />. It was estimated that geothermal heat pumps had, in 2015, a total capacity of about {{val|50|u=GW}} producing about {{convert|455|PJ|TWh}} per year <ref name=\"WWGeo2015\">{{cite journal |first1= John W. |last1= Lund |first2= Tonya L. |last2= Boyd |date= March 2016 |title= Direct utilization of geothermal energy 2015 worldwide review |pages= 66\u201393 |journal= Geothermics|volume= 60|doi= 10.1016/j.geothermics.2015.11.004}}</ref>.\n\n==== Bio energy ====\n{{Main|Biomass|Biogas|Biofuel}}\n\nUntil the beginning of the nineteenth century biomass was the predominant fuel, today it has only a small share of the overall energy supply. Electricity produced from [[biomass]] sources was estimated at 44&nbsp;GW for 2005. Biomass electricity generation increased by over 100% in Germany, Hungary, the Netherlands, Poland, and Spain. A further 220&nbsp;GW was used for heating (in 2004), bringing the total energy consumed from biomass to around 264&nbsp;GW. The use of biomass fires for cooking is excluded.<ref name=\"Renewables2006\" /> World production of [[Ethanol fuel|bioethanol]] increased by 8% in 2005 to reach {{convert|33|GL|usgal|lk=on}}, with most of the increase in the United States, bringing it level to the levels of consumption in Brazil.<ref name=\"Renewables2006\" /> [[Biodiesel]] increased by 85% to {{convert|3.9|GL|usgal}}, making it the fastest growing renewable energy source in 2005. Over 50% is produced in Germany.<ref name=\"Renewables2006\" />\n\n== By country ==\n{{Main|List of renewable energy topics by country}}\n{{See also|:category:Energy by country|l1=Energy by country|Worldwide energy supply|List of countries by energy consumption per capita}}\n\n{{Pie chart\n| thumb =right\n| caption =World total final consumption of 9,717 [[Tonne of oil equivalent|Mtoe]] by region in 2017 (IEA, 2019)<ref name=\"IEA-Report-keyworld-2019\"/>\n| other = \n| label1 =[[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development|OECD]]\n| value1 =38.2\n| color1 =#66CCFF\n| label2 =Middle East\n| value2 =5.1\n| color2 =#FFFF57 \n| label3 =Non-OECD Eurasia\n| value3 =7.5\n| color3 =#009a39\n| label4 =China\n| value4 =20.6\n| color4 =#de2821\n| label5 = Rest of Asia\n| value5 =13.5\n| color5 =pink\n| label6 =Non-OECD Americas\n| value6 =4.8\n| color6 =#211873\n| label7 =Africa\n| value7 =6.1\n| color7 =#ef8e39\n| label8 =International aviation and marine bunkers\n| value8 =4.2\n| color8 =#313c42\n}}\n[[File:Global energy consumption.jpg|thumb|right|World energy consumption per capita, 1950\u20132004]]\n\nEnergy consumption is loosely correlated with [[Gross National Product#Gross National Product|gross national product]] and climate, but there is a large difference even between the most highly developed countries, such as Japan and Germany with an energy consumption rate of 6&nbsp;kW per person and the [[Energy use in the United States|United States]] with an energy consumption rate of 11.4&nbsp;kW per person. In developing countries, particularly those that are sub-tropical or tropical such as India, the per person energy use rate is closer to 0.7&nbsp;kW. Bangladesh has the lowest consumption rate with 0.2&nbsp;kW per person.\n\nThe US consumes 25% of the world's energy with a share of global GDP at 22% and a share of the world population at 4.6%.<ref name=\"World Population Prospects\">{{cite web |url= http://esa.un.org/UNPP/ |title= World Population Prospects |publisher= United Nations |accessdate= 7 February 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070321013235/http://esa.un.org/unpp/ |archive-date= 21 March 2007 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The most significant growth of energy consumption is currently taking place in China, which has been growing at 5.5% per year over the last 25 years. Its population of 1.3 billion people (19.6% of the world population<ref name=\"World Population Prospects\" />) is consuming energy at a rate of 1.6&nbsp;kW per person.\n\nOne measurement of efficiency is [[energy intensity]]. This is a measure of the amount of energy it takes a country to produce a dollar of gross domestic product.\n\n{{multiple image\n |direction = horizontal\n |align= center\n |width1= 255\n |width2= 250\n |image1=Energy Use per Capita.png\n |image2=GDP per unit of energy use.png\n |caption1=The World Bank: Kilograms of oil equivalent (2011)\n |caption2=The World Bank: PPP $ per kg of oil equivalent (2011)\n}}\n{{clear left}}\n\n=== Oil ===\n\n{{Main|Petroleum}}\n\nSaudi Arabia, Russia and the United States accounted for 34% of oil production in 2011. Saudi Arabia, Russia and Nigeria accounted for 36% of oil export in 2011.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatleft\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|+ Top 10 [[oil]] producers (Mt)<ref name=IEA2013/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank\n! scope=\"col\" | Nation\n! scope=\"col\" | 2005\n! scope=\"col\" | 2008\n! scope=\"col\" | 2009\n! scope=\"col\" | 2010\n! scope=\"col\" | 2011\n! scope=\"col\" | Share %<br/>2011\n! scope=\"col\" | 2012\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Saudi Arabia|Saudi Arabia]]\n|   519 ||   509 ||   452 ||   471 ||   517 || 12.9% || 544\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Russia|Russia]]\n|   470 ||   485 ||   494 ||   502 ||   510 || 12.7% || 520\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in the United States|United States]]\n|   307 ||   300 ||   320 ||   336 ||   346 ||  8.6% || 387\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Iran|Iran]]\n|   205 ||   214 ||   206 ||   227 ||   215 ||  5.4% || 186\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in China|China]]\n|   183 ||   190 ||   194 ||   200 ||   203 ||  5.1% || 206\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Canada|Canada]]\n|   143 ||   155 ||   152 ||   159 ||   169 ||  4.2% || 182\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in the United Arab Emirates|UAE]]\n|    nd ||   136 ||   120 ||   129 ||   149 ||  3.7% || 163\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Venezuela|Venezuela]]\n|   162 ||   137 ||   126 ||   149 ||   148 ||  3.7% || 162\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Mexico|Mexico]]\n|   188 ||   159 ||   146 ||   144 ||   144 ||  3.6% ||  nd\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Energy in Nigeria|Nigeria]]\n|   133 ||    nd ||    nd ||   130 ||   139 ||  3.5% ||  nd\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | x\n| style=\"text